du, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bechton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern) and Scottish: habitational name from Beckton near Lockerbie in Dumfriesshire. The placename is from Old Norse <i>bekkr</i> ‘beck, stream’, + <i>tūn</i> ‘farm, village’. The surname is not from Beckton in East Ham (Essex), which is named for the 19th-century gas and coal magnate S. A. Beck. Compare   Becton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Becton","meanings":["Scottish and English: altered form of   Beckton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Bechton II was born about 1262, in Bechton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert de Bechton I and Mrs. Robert de Bechton. He married Mrs Robert De Bechton II about 1287, in Hankelow, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1262–":"umbes 1262–Surnud","1262–Male":"1262–Surnud","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1316":"1316","ABT 1262":"umbes 1262","Abt 1287":"umbes 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","before 1262":"enne 1262","1275":"1275","about 1299":"umbes 1299","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Bechton, Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Bechton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1262–":"noin 1262–Kuollut","1262–Male":"1262–Kuollut","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","1299–Female":"1299–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1316":"1316","ABT 1262":"noin 1262","Abt 1287":"noin 1287","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","before 1262":"ennen vuotta 1262","1275":"1275","about 1299":"noin 1299","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe","Bechton, Sandbach, Cheshire, England":"Bechton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hankelow, Cheshire":"Hankelow, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1262–":"environ 1262–Décédé","1262–Male":"1262–Décédé","1275–1316":"1275–1316","1265–Female":"1265–Décédée","1299–Female":"1299–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1316":"1316","ABT 1262":"environ 1262","Abt 1287":"environ 